"Schaeffer M., Selten F.M., Opsteegh J.D., Goosse H.","The influence of ocean convection patterns on high-latitude climate projections",2004,"Journal of Climate","17","22",,"4316","4329",,,10.1175/3174.1,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-11044227343&partnerID=40&md5=809adae41aa9510c2bd5816b6279d927","Royal Netherlands Meteorol. Inst., De Bilt, Netherlands; Natl. Inst. of Pub. Hlth./the Envrn., RIVM, PO Box 1, 3720 BA Bilthoven, Netherlands; Universite Catholique de Louvain, Louvain-la-Neuve, Belgium","Schaeffer, M., Royal Netherlands Meteorol. Inst., De Bilt, Netherlands, Natl. Inst. of Pub. Hlth./the Envrn., RIVM, PO Box 1, 3720 BA Bilthoven, Netherlands; Selten, F.M., Royal Netherlands Meteorol. Inst., De Bilt, Netherlands; Opsteegh, J.D., Royal Netherlands Meteorol. Inst., De Bilt, Netherlands; Goosse, H., Universite Catholique de Louvain, Louvain-la-Neuve, Belgium","The mean state and variability of deep convection in the ocean influence the North Atlantic climate. Using an ensemble experiment with a coupled atmosphere-ocean-sea ice model, it is shown that cooling and subdued warming areas can occur over the North Atlantic Ocean and adjacent landmasses under global warming. Different ""present-day"" convection patterns in the Greenland-Iceland-Norway (GIN) Sea result in different future surface-air temperature changes. At higher latitudes, the more effective positive sea ice feedback increases the likelihood of changes in convection causing a regional cooling that is larger than the warming brought about by the enhanced greenhouse effect. The modeled freshening of deep ocean layers in the North Atlantic in a time period preceding a reorganization of GIN Sea convection is consistent with recent observations. Low-frequency internal variability in the ocean model has relatively little impact on the response patterns. © 2004 American Meteorological Society.",,"Global warming; Greenhouse effect; Heat convection; Mathematical models; Ocean currents; 